WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hi, everyone. My name is Luis. I'm a biologist. I study mammals.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
I do research in ecology and evolution. But as part of my work,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
I'm often helping students and colleagues with their analysis.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
And this involves a lot of running and explaining and fixing code that I didn't write myself.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So, by the way, in this research setting, people tend to work interactively with scripts.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.000
And there they'll be loading different packages to do different things.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Sometimes I'll recognize the names and what they're for, but a lot of the times I won't.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
That's fine. No one's expected to know all about the tens of thousands of packages out there.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And I'm not the only one that sometimes needs clarification, right?

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Like this user here. His grammar, not mine. That's my talk title.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
So say we're loading some packages in a script like here.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
So my practice nowadays is to ask the people I'm working with,

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
what are these for or is there anything I should know about them?

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And if so, let's just go ahead and add these little code comments.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And at least to me, this is already giving me a pretty good idea of what's going to happen later on in the script.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And I know that this conflicts with good practices of not adding too many code comments.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
But in my opinion, these little package comments are fairly unobtrusive.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
And we're loading packages once per script ideally, so it's not too much clutter.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
I think it's okay to do.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.000
And if I'm asking people to add these comments to their code,

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
then I should help create them or do something to automate these comments.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
So what I did was to develop some tools that can build these comments,

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
either by pulling information from package descriptions,

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
or just checking a script to see how the different package elements are used.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And after that, I wanted to examine comments in public code to see if people are doing more or less this overall.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
So here's the tool I built for this. It's the Annotator R package.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
It can add various bits of information to library load calls.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
So let me just show you.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Through either functions or add-ins, we can do things like add the package title next to each call.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:17.000
And package titles are usually short and informative, in my opinion.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Or we can list the exported functions from each package if they appear in a script.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Or this one that I use a lot, which adds versions and sources.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
So now I've seen comments like this here and there, especially in blogs and teaching materials,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
but I wanted to check thoroughly.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So what I did was to search a snapshot of public GitHub repositories.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
The details for this are in my blog, but of about half a million relevant files,

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
I located 4,000 comments I could look at.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
I'm not naming package names here, just the comments,

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:00.000
but overall people are mentioning the overall purpose of their packages or any functions of interest,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
which was a good thing to know.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
A fair amount of comments about pipes for some reason,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
and people leaving various technical details.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Here's a few more that I found amusing.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.000
I'm not naming names here as well.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
You can guess, try and guess which package those are for.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
But now let me just leave you to at least consider adding these sorts of comments to your code,

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
especially if it's meant to be read by others.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
This is a low effort thing to do with a potential high reward,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
and it's like with this baby drawing here.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
If we know what the little kid is trying to draw,

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
then we might see them see and recognize the elements sooner.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And same thing with code, I think.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So if we provide some context and intention,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
we'll be reducing the amount of guesswork and interpretation that people will do

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
when they encounter new code that they haven't seen before.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So yeah, we should do this to give users of our code a head start.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
That's it for me, so catch me outside if you want.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Thank you.

